               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-247-person1384">
                  WILLIAM 
                  DOYLE
               <interp inst="t18280911-247-person1384" type="surname" value="DOYLE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-247-person1384" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-247-person1384" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am partner with my father, John Doyle, he is a <rs id="t18280911-247-viclabel1266" type="occupation">fan-light maker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280911-247-victim1383 t18280911-247-viclabel1266"></join>. We missed some sashes on the 16th of August - the prisoner was our <rs id="t18280911-247-deflabel1267" type="occupation">apprentice</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280911-247-defend1382 t18280911-247-deflabel1267"></join> - these sashes which are here, correspond with those in our stock; I measured them, and I know we had sashes like those; we missed sixteen of them; the circumstance of one sash being found with Baker, led us to look, and then we missed them. (see Page 838)</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. Did you see the prisoner take any sashes? A. No.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-247-person1385">
                  HENRY 
                  HERRING
               <interp inst="t18280911-247-person1385" type="surname" value="HERRING"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-247-person1385" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-247-person1385" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a labourer. On the 16th of August, about nine o'clock in the morning, the prisoner came to our house at Somers'-town with these two sashes, and asked him to let him leave them for a short time; I let him leave them, as I thought he might have a job in the town; I afterwards gave them to the constable.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-247-person1386">
                  SAMUEL 
                  SHUTTLEWORTH
               <interp inst="t18280911-247-person1386" type="surname" value="SHUTTLEWORTH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-247-person1386" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-247-person1386" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I received these two sashes from Herring - Green took up the prisoner; Herring had been to Mrs. Baker's once or twice to know what was to be done with them, and Mrs. Baker went to Herring's, and said "For God's sake! break the glass and burn the frames.</p>
               <p>MR. PHILLIPS to HENRY HERRING. Q. We have heard that you went once or twice to Mrs. Baker's? A. Yes, I am sure it was not Baker who left them, but I went to know who Christmas' master was; I went there again, because she said her son could tell me.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I do not know the young man at all.</p>
               <p>The prisoner received a good character.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18280911-247-verdict1268" type="verdictDescription">
